explanation:
To check whether the pointer usage in OS_TaskSetPriority_Impl conforms to the MISRA rule that pointers should point to const-qualified types whenever possible, the analyser must know the exact types and const-qualification of the token and any functions/macros that consume it:

- OS_object_token_t (typedef/definition): Determines whether the token is an object that should be const-qualified and whether it itself contains pointers or mutable fields. You must know the underlying type to reason about whether it is mutated.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro or function definition/expansion): This macro/function is used with *token. Its expansion may perform writes or take a non-const parameter; knowing its signature/behavior is required to decide if token must be non-const or can be const.

- OS_impl_task_table (declaration/type of the table): The table type can influence how OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET/lookup is invoked (by value, by pointer, constness expectations). It may determine whether the lookup dereferences or modifies the token value.

- OS_impl_task_internal_record_t (struct definition): Needed to see the types of fields (e.g. impl->id) and whether any pointer fields are involved that could be affected by const qualification decisions or by indirect modification of token-derived data.

- OS_ObjectIdFromToken (function prototype/signature): The code passes token to this function. Its parameter type must be known (const-qualified or not) to determine if passing a const OS_object_token_t * is valid and whether the function could legally modify the token data.

- OS_ObjectIdToInteger (function prototype/signature): Although it likely just converts an ID, its parameter type will show whether it accepts the output of OS_ObjectIdFromToken and whether any further const-correctness implications arise.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (function prototype/signature, if used by the table/macro): The static call graph shows this symbol as related to object-token indexing. If OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET expands to or calls this, its parameter constness and semantics are necessary to conclude whether token should be const or non-const.

Collecting these symbols lets the next analyser determine whether the token pointer and any other pointers used in the function are appropriately const-qualified or must be non-const because they are modified by the called macros/functions.
